just_use events.go

# label: VESTIGIAL
# role: encodes domain knowledge — legacy diff-based host flow

**Status note (2026-04-19):** this module is mostly legacy. The
diff-based host flow it describes (`CheckEvent`,
`ParseMoveEvent`, `ReconstructBoard`, the `wire*` types with
`stacks_to_remove` / `stacks_to_add`) was load-bearing for
the old game-replay UI that was ripped in bcaea72
(2026-04-18). The current Elm LynRummy session flow is
action-based: `WireAction` → `DecodeWireAction` →
`lynrummy_elm_actions` table → `ReplayActionsSeeded` for
replay.

Retain for now because `GameSetup` (exported) is still used by
the dealer path, and because any remaining non-lyn-rummy
consumers in the host (if any) would break on removal.
Candidate for a scorched-earth cleanup pass when the retire
list is audited.

## What still matters here

- `GameSetup` — the "photo" the dealer returns. Pre-dates the
  wire-action format but is still the shape that
  `BuildDoubleDeck` / `DealFullGame` produce.
- Package-internal helpers that happen to be co-located.

## What is dead or dying

- `CheckEvent`, `ParseMoveEvent`, `ReconstructBoard` — the
  diff-based host dispatch. Not called from the new
  Elm-session flow. If a consumer still calls it, that
  consumer is on the ripped code path.
- `wire*` diff structs (`wireBoardEvent`, `wireMoveEvent`,
  etc.). Superseded by `WireAction` in `wire_action.go`.

## Drift caveat

The original sidecar described `CheckEvent` as "the single
entry point the Host (games package) calls" — that host is
the one that was ripped. Future-Claude investigating events.go
should verify current consumers (`grep -rn 'CheckEvent\|ReconstructBoard'`)
before changing anything; may turn out to have zero live
call-sites and be fully deletable.
